tutorial_T1800 compresses the entire order book into a single number (mid) and throws away everything else. Here are strategies that use what it discards:

1. Book imbalance (available every tick)

bid_vol = sum of all bid volumes
ask_vol = sum of all ask volumes  
imbalance = (bid_vol - ask_vol) / (bid_vol + ask_vol)
If bids are heavier than asks, there's more demand → price likely rises. This is a leading indicator — volume shifts before price moves. Roy's tut.py already uses a version of this (L1+L2 composite). tutorial_T1800 ignores volumes completely.

2. Microprice (available every tick)

microprice = (bid * ask_vol + ask * bid_vol) / (bid_vol + ask_vol)
Weights toward the thinner side of the book. If asks are thin (few sellers), microprice pulls toward the ask → bullish. More responsive than mid because it reacts to volume changes, not just price changes. The mid only moves when bid/ask prices move; microprice moves when volumes shift.

3. Spread narrowing direction (available every tick)
The spread is normally 13–14 (bot walls at ±7). When it narrows to 5–9, a third participant posted a tight quote. Which side they posted on is directional:

Tight ask (someone posting a low sell) → selling pressure, bearish
Tight bid (someone posting a high buy) → buying pressure, bullish
Track best_ask - mid vs mid - best_bid. When asymmetric, the tight side is where the action is.

4. Own-trade fill asymmetry (available most ticks)

recent_buy_fills = volume of our buys that filled last N ticks
recent_sell_fills = volume of our sells that filled last N ticks
If our sells keep filling but our buys don't, it means buyers are aggressively hitting us → bullish. If our buys keep filling → sellers hitting us → bearish. This is available from own_trades and is more frequent than market_trades.

5. Volume acceleration (available every tick)
Track total book volume (all bids + all asks) over time. If volume is shrinking, liquidity is thinning → larger price move is imminent. Doesn't tell direction, but combined with imbalance it becomes: "imbalance is bullish AND volume is thinning → expect a move UP."

What tutorial_T1800 has vs what it needs
tutorial_T1800 has: a lagging 1D signal (mid price → MA → FV). It sees direction only after the price has already moved.

What it's missing: a leading multi-dimensional signal. The book imbalance and microprice shift BEFORE the mid price moves — they're where the information lives. The MA only sees the result after the fact.